          "body": "Verse 11 is the psalm's structural hinge. After nine verses of rescue-memory and praise, the psalmist turns on the pivot of a confident petition: 'You, O LORD, will not withhold Your compassion from me; Your lovingkindness and Your truth will continually preserve me.' The grammar is assertive, almost defiant — not a wish but a declaration of confidence in God's covenant character. Then v. 12 discloses why the petition is needed: 'evils beyond number have surrounded me; my iniquities have overtaken me, so that I am not able to see.' The word 'iniquities' (*avan*) is arresting — David is not blaming only enemies. He confesses his own moral weight has caught up with him. The phrase 'more numerous than the hairs of my head' (40:12) mirrors the uncountable wonders of v. 5, creating a grim inversion: God's wonders are innumerable, and so are my sins. Only the God of v. 5 is sufficient for the David of v. 12."
